## 1. One-Line Summary

- The Hook — Tenergy 05 is the undisputed gold standard of modern topspin play, offering an unmatched combination of heavy spin, a high arc, and a dynamic catapult effect.
- Archetype — Aggressive Looper / Two-Winged Topspin Attacker.

---

## 2. Performance Analysis

- Speed & Gears
    - Passive Block Speed: Bouncy and fast. The Spring Sponge activates easily, meaning passive blocks can sometimes pop up or go long if the racket angle isn't perfectly calibrated.
    - Active Loop Speed: Extremely high. When you engage the sponge, the speed curve spikes, delivering devastating pace on offensive strokes.
    - Linearity vs. Trampoline: Highly non-linear (trampoline effect). Players must adjust to the sudden surge in power when the ball bites deeply into the sponge.
    - Mid-Distance Carry: Exceptional. The high tension ensures that balls looped from mid-distance easily carry deep into the opponent's side of the table without requiring maximum physical exertion.

- Spin Generation
    - Top-End Spin: Legendary. Tenergy 05 grips the ball aggressively, producing some of the heaviest topspin available outside of tacky Chinese rubbers.
    - Opening Loop: Effortless. The high throw angle and grip make lifting heavy backspin almost automatic.
    - Serve Quality: Fantastic grip allows for massive spin variation on serves, though the bounciness requires a delicate touch to keep them short.

- Control & Short Game
    - Touch Play: Demanding. The rubber is very lively, requiring soft hands and precise technique to execute tight drop shots.
    - Spin Sensitivity: Extremely high. It grips everything—meaning you generate massive spin, but you are also highly susceptible to incoming spin if your angle is off.
    - Flick Window: Narrow but lethal. The banana flick (Chiquita) is a dream with this rubber, but flat flicks require perfect timing.

- Throw Angle (Arc)
    - Trajectory: High and pronounced.
    - Arc Behavior: The ball arcs high over the net and dips sharply onto the table, providing excellent safety margins for aggressive loopers.

- Spin-Interaction Behavior
    - Against Heavy Topspin: Requires a very closed racket angle and active forward stroke to counter the incoming spin; otherwise, the ball will fly long.
    - Against Heavy Backspin: Thrives against backspin. The rubber naturally wants to lift the ball, turning defensive chops into aggressive topspin drives.
    - Error Pattern: Most unforced errors will be overshooting the baseline due to the trampoline effect or popping the ball up due to high spin sensitivity.

