## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

- Serve: Delivers tremendous spin, but requires advanced brushing technique to prevent the sponge from catapulting the ball long.

- Receive
    - Push/Stop: Needs a very soft touch. Aggressive pushing can easily drift long.
    - Flick: Forehand flicks need a good brush; flat slapping is risky.
    - Chiquita/Banana: Absolutely world-class. The high throw and grip make wrapping around the ball incredibly effective.

- Loop/Drive
    - First Loop (3rd Ball): Phenomenal. Lifting backspin is its primary strength, offering immense safety over the net.
    - Continuous Looping: The bread and butter of T05. It encourages continuous, relentless topspin rallies.
    - Power Loop / Kill: Devastating, though flatter kills are less forgiving than highly brushed power loops.

- Countering
    - Counter-Topspin: Excellent when actively brushed with a closed angle. Passive countering results in the ball flying off the table.
    - Punch Counter / Active Block: Decent, but the rubber prefers a looping motion over a flat punch.

- Blocking
    - Passive Block: Tricky. The high spin sensitivity and bounce require micro-adjustments to the blade angle.
    - Active Block: Much better. Adding a little topspin or actively pressing forward neutralizes the trampoline effect.

- Smash & Flat Hit: Below average. The rubber is built for spin; flat hits can feel erratic due to the high arc and sponge tension.

- Defense
    - Chop: Only viable for desperation or highly skilled defenders. Generally too bouncy for modern defense.
    - Lob: Outstanding. The catapult effect allows you to return balls high and deep from far behind the table with ease.

